\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What is the technology scope and language technologies are used by big names like Wordpress.com and similar big names to establish and develop their platform inside their SaaS applications\
\
The "big names" in the website building SaaS space (like WordPress.com, Wix, Squarespace, and Shopify) rely on massive, industrial-grade technology stacks. While they all aim to make things simple for the user, their underlying "Technology Scope" is vast, usually splitting into a 
\f1\b Frontend
\f0\b0  (what users see) and a 
\f1\b Backend
\f0\b0  (the brain and storage).
\fs32 \cf3 \cb4 \super \strokec3 1
\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Here is the breakdown of the specific languages and technologies used by these giants to build their platforms.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 1. WordPress.com (Automattic)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 It is important to distinguish between the open-source WordPress software and the 
\f1\b WordPress.com
\f0\b0  SaaS platform. The SaaS version wraps the open-source core in a modern, high-performance interface.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Core Backend Language:
\f0\b0  
\f1\b PHP
\f0\b0 . This is the historic foundation of WordPress. It is mature, runs on almost all servers, and powers the core logic of the site.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The "SaaS" Interface (Calypso):
\f0\b0  
\f1\b JavaScript (React.js)
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b Node.js
\f0\b0 .
\fs32 \cf3 \cb4 \super \strokec3 2
\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1
\f2\i \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f3\i0 \uc0\u9702 
\f2\i 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Why this matters:
\f0\i0  The WordPress.com dashboard you use to manage your site is actually a separate application (codenamed "Calypso") built entirely in JavaScript. It communicates with your PHP website remotely via an API. This makes the dashboard feel instant and "app-like," rather than reloading pages constantly like the old WordPress dashboard.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Database:
\f0\b0  
\f1\b MySQL
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b MariaDB
\f0\b0 .
\fs32 \cf3 \cb4 \super \strokec3 3
\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \strokec2  This is where all the text, user data, and settings are stored.\uc0\u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Web Server:
\f0\b0  
\f1\b NGINX
\f0\b0 .
\fs32 \cf3 \cb4 \super \strokec3 4
\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \nosupersub \strokec2  Used for high performance and handling massive traffic loads (replacing the older Apache server in many big setups).\uc0\u8232 \
