\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 Why is this "Scalable" if it's simple?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 You might worry this is "too simple" compared to the Pod architecture of Shopify. Here is why this specific setup scales:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The "Monorepo" Advantage:
\f0\b0  Because Next.js keeps your frontend and backend in one folder, you can build features fast. When you eventually get huge, you can "eject" the backend into a separate Node.js service without changing the frontend language.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Serverless Database:
\f0\b0  Services like Supabase or Neon handle the "Podding" and complex data stuff for you. You just pay more as you grow; you don't have to hire a database engineer.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Edge Network:
\f0\b0  Vercel (and competitors like Netlify) serve your site from the "Edge" (servers all over the world), similar to how Squarespace loads quickly everywhere.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

